---
import BaseHead from "../components/BaseHead.astro";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
import { SITE_TITLE, SITE_DESCRIPTION } from "../consts";
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead title={SITE_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION} />
    <style>
      body {
        font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
        background-color: #f4f4f4;
        color: #333;
      }

      .home-container {
        max-width: 1200px;
        margin: 0 auto;
        padding: 20px;
      }

      .intro,
      .beer-styles,
      .glassware,
      .about-site,
      .taste-profiles {
        background-color: #ffffff;
        padding: 20px;
        margin-bottom: 20px;
        border-radius: 8px;
        box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
      }

      h1,
      h2 {
        color: #007bff;
        margin-top: 0;
      }

      ul {
        padding-left: 20px;
      }

      ul li {
        margin-bottom: 10px;
      }

      p {
        line-height: 1.6;
      }

      @media (max-width: 768px) {
        .home-container {
          padding: 10px;
        }

        ul {
          padding-left: 15px;
        }

        ul li {
          font-size: 14px;
        }
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <Header />
    <main>
      <div class="home-container">
        <section class="intro">
          <h1>Welcome to Beer Ratings</h1>
          <p>
            Discover and compare ratings of various beers, explore different
            styles, and find the best glassware for your favorite brews. Whether
            you're an aficionado or just getting started, this site is your
            guide to the world of beer.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="beer-styles">
          <h2>Beer Styles</h2>
          <p>
            Beer comes in a wide variety of styles, each with its own unique
            flavors, aromas, and characteristics. Here are some popular styles:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>IPA (India Pale Ale)</strong> - Known for its hoppy bitterness
              and fruity notes. Often served in a tulip or pint glass.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Lager</strong> - A crisp and refreshing style, usually light
              in flavor. Best enjoyed in a pint glass or a mug.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Stout</strong> - Rich, dark, and creamy with flavors of coffee
              or chocolate. Serve in a snifter or a tulip glass.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Saison</strong> - A farmhouse ale with spicy and fruity flavors.
              Typically served in a tulip or snifter.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Pilsner</strong> - A light and refreshing lager with a slightly
              bitter finish. Perfect in a pilsner glass.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Wheat Beer</strong> - Light and cloudy with a citrusy flavor,
              often served in a weizen glass.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="taste-profiles">
          <h2>Taste Profiles</h2>
          <p>
            Each beer style has its own distinct taste profile, which can range
            from sweet and malty to bitter and hoppy. Understanding these
            profiles can help you better appreciate the nuances of different
            beers:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Hoppy</strong> - Common in IPAs and Pale Ales, with strong
              flavors of citrus, pine, or herbal notes. Often bitter but can also
              have fruity undertones.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Malty</strong> - Found in styles like Bocks and Porters, offering
              sweet flavors reminiscent of caramel, toffee, or chocolate. Provides
              a rich and smooth mouthfeel.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Fruity</strong> - Typical in Belgian Ales and certain Sours,
              with flavors ranging from citrus and berries to tropical fruits. Can
              be sweet or tart.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Spicy</strong> - Present in styles like Saisons and some Belgian
              Ales, featuring flavors of pepper, clove, or coriander. Adds a zesty,
              warming character.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Roasty</strong> - Characteristic of Stouts and Porters, offering
              deep flavors of coffee, espresso, or dark chocolate. Often associated
              with a dry finish.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Sour/Tart</strong> - Found in Sour Ales and Lambics, with a
              sharp, tangy flavor that can range from mildly acidic to intensely
              sour.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Smoky</strong> - Seen in Rauchbiers and some Scotch Ales, delivering
              flavors reminiscent of smoked meat or wood. Adds a complex, savory
              depth.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="glassware">
          <h2>Beer Glassware</h2>
          <p>
            Choosing the right glassware for your beer can enhance its flavors
            and aroma. Here are some common types of beer glasses:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Pint Glass</strong> - A versatile glass used for many styles,
              especially IPAs and lagers.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Snifter</strong> - Ideal for strong ales and stouts, concentrating
              the beer's aroma.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Tulip Glass</strong> - Great for Belgian ales and IPAs, with
              a wide body and flared lip to capture aroma.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Weizen Glass</strong> - Tall and slender, perfect for wheat
              beers, with a shape that supports the beer's foam.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Pilsner Glass</strong> - Narrow and tall, enhancing the appearance
              of pilsners and lagers.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Mug</strong> - Thick-walled and sturdy, often used for lagers
              and other session beers.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="about-site">
          <h2>About This Site</h2>
          <p>
            This website is designed to help beer enthusiasts explore and
            compare different beers based on ratings. Whether you're looking for
            the top-rated beers or learning more about various beer styles and
            glassware, this site is your ultimate beer companion.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
